<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The Equal Rights Amendment (ERA) in the 1920s was:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Successfully ratified into law</option>
            <option letter="b">Opposed by many women's groups</option>
            <option letter="c">Supported by conservative Republicans</option>
            <option letter="d">Focused on voting rights</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Equal Rights Amendment, proposed by Alice Paul in 1923, faced significant opposition from women's groups and labor organizations who feared it would eliminate protective legislation for working women. This split in the women's movement reflected broader disagreements about equality versus protection, as many activists worried the ERA would hurt working-class women by removing special workplace protections.</explanation>
    </question>
